fessionals and settlers continually innovated plans for both rural and urban frontiers in response to the competing demands of social and political ideologies and the need to achieve productivity, economic independence, and security in a hostile environment. In the 1930s, security became the primary challenge, shaping and even distorting patterns of growth.Not until the 1993 Oslo Accords, with prospects of compromise and accommodation, did planners again imagine Israel as a normal state, developing like other modern societies. Troen concludes that if Palestinian Arabs become reconciled to a Jewish state, Israel will reassign priority to the social and economic development of the country and region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgricultural coloniesxHistoryxPalestine. 0aAgricultural colonieszPalestinexHistory. 0aJewsxColonizationxHistoryxPalestine. 0aJewsxColonizationzPalestinexHistory. 0aJewsxEconomic conditionsx19th centuryxPalestine. 0aJewsxEconomic conditionsx20th centuryxIsrael. 0aJewszIsraelxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aJewszPalestinexEconomic conditionsy19th century. 0aKibbutzimxHistory. 0aMoshavimxHistory. 0aUrbanizationxHistoryxIsraelxIsraelxMiddle EastxPalestine. 0aUrbanizationzIsraelxHistory. 0aZionismxHistoryxPalestine. 0aZionismzPalestinexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300128000423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300128000.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 20